      "title": "Cookie Scope: Domain and Path"
    },
    {
      "description": "Cookie security attributes: Secure, HttpOnly, and SameSite flags that protect cookies from theft and misuse.",
      "title": "Cookie Security Attributes"
    },
    {
      "description": "Common cookie use cases: session management, user preferences, and tracking.",
      "title": "Common Cookie Use Cases"
    },
    {
      "description": "What a Content Delivery Network is: a geographically distributed group of servers that deliver cached content from locations closer to users.",
      "title": "What Is a CDN?"
    },
    {
      "description": "How CDNs use edge servers placed in many locations worldwide to reduce latency for end users.",
      "title": "CDN Edge Servers"
    },
    {
      "description": "How a CDN decides which edge server handles a request using geographic and performance-based routing.",
      "title": "CDN Request Routing"
    },
    {
      "description": "The types of content CDNs serve best: static assets like images, CSS, JavaScript, and video.",
      "title": "What CDNs Cache"
    },
    {
      "description": "How CDNs handle cache invalidation: purging stale content and refreshing edge caches with updated resources.",
      "title": "CDN Cache Invalidation"
    },
    {
      "description": "Key benefits of CDNs: reduced latency, lower origin server load, improved availability, and DDoS mitigation.",
      "title": "CDN Benefits"
    },
    {
      "description": "How all the pieces fit together: a client resolves DNS, establishes a TLS connection, sends an HTTP request through possible proxies and CDNs, and receives a response.",
      "title": "Putting It All Together: A Web Request Lifecycle"
    }
  ]
}

